      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"workouts\":[{\"day_of_week\":1,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Return Run – Monday\",\"target_distance_km\":3,\"target_duration_minutes\":20,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":358,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":358,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start with 3 minutes of brisk walking to warm up the foot and ankle. Pay attention to any stiffness in the right heel — this is normal early on and should ease within the first few minutes.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":14,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Run easy at 5:58/km. If any foot pain arises above a 2/10, transition immediately to a walk until it subsides, then resume running. Keep effort conversational — you should be able to speak in full sentences.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Finish with 3 minutes of easy walking. Gently roll the foot or do a light calf stretch after stopping — this helps manage plantar fascia tension post-run.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Walk for 3 minutes before you begin running. If the foot feels stiff, extend the walk to 5 minutes. There's no rush here — a proper warmup is doing real work.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk for at least 3 minutes after finishing. Avoid sitting down immediately. A gentle standing calf stretch (both straight-leg and bent-knee) held for 30 seconds each side is a great habit to build post-run.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"James, this is your first run of the new week and the goal is simple: keep the foot happy and keep the aerobic engine ticking. Your recent sessions have been really encouraging — no pain on March 17th and only mild stiffness on March 10th that resolved quickly. That's a great sign. This run mirrors what's been working: 20 minutes at 5:58/km, easy effort, with permission to walk any time the foot asks for it. The physiotherapist has cleared you for exactly this, so trust the process. Fitness will come back faster than you think once the foot is fully settled.\",\"perceived_effort\":3},{\"day_of_week\":3,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Mid-Week Easy Run – Wednesday\",\"target_distance_km\":3,\"target_duration_minutes\":20,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":358,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":358,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Begin with 3 minutes of walking. Notice how the foot feels compared to Monday — any lingering soreness from earlier in the week is worth noting mentally.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":14,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy running at 5:58/km. This is a maintenance run — not a fitness-building run. The goal is consistency and foot tolerance, not pace or distance. Walk breaks are always available and never a setback.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"3 minutes of easy walking to close out. Check in with how the foot feels — any soreness that lingers more than 30 minutes post-run is worth flagging to your physio.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"3-minute walk warmup. If Monday's run left any residual foot soreness, extend the walk to 5–7 minutes and keep the running portion shorter if needed. Your body's feedback is always the most important data point.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk 3 minutes, then do your post-run calf and plantar fascia stretches. Consistency with these makes a real difference over weeks, not just days.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Wednesday sits in the middle of your week and serves as a gentle aerobic stimulus between Monday and Saturday. The key here is that this run should feel easier than Monday — your body has had two days to recover. If it doesn't feel easier, that's useful information worth paying attention to. Everything stays at 5:58/km easy pace, 20 minutes max, with walk breaks as needed. No speed work, no pushing — your physio has been clear and that guidance is there to protect the progress you've already made.\",\"perceived_effort\":3},{\"day_of_week\":6,\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"title\":\"Saturday Long Run – Easy Effort\",\"target_distance_km\":4,\"target_duration_minutes\":20,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":358,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":358,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":4,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start with a 4-minute walk. Saturday runs can carry more fatigue from the week, so give the foot a little extra time to warm up. No rushing into the run.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":12,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy running at 5:58/km. This is your 'long run' for the week — but at this stage of return, that simply means the most important run of the week, not the longest or hardest. Stay easy, stay present, and walk any time the foot signals discomfort.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":4,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"4-minute walk cooldown. Take your time here. Saturday is a good day to do a slightly longer post-run stretch routine if you have the time — calf raises, toe stretches, and a gentle foot massage can all support plantar fascia recovery.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Walk for 4 minutes before running. Saturday is your designated long run day, and even though the duration is capped at 20 minutes right now, treating it with the same ritual as a long run — proper warmup, mindful effort, thorough cooldown — builds good habits for when volume increases.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk for at least 4 minutes. If you have time, a 10-minute post-run routine of calf stretches, seated toe stretches, and a gentle foot roller or frozen water bottle roll under the arch can meaningfully support your plantar fascia recovery between sessions.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Saturday is your long run anchor — and even at 20 minutes, it matters. Physiologically, this run reinforces the aerobic adaptations from Monday and Wednesday and gives your connective tissue a slightly longer loading stimulus, which is exactly what plantar fascia recovery needs: progressive, controlled stress followed by adequate rest. The pace stays at 5:58/km — the easy end of your training range — because the goal right now is tissue tolerance, not cardiovascular challenge. You've built a really solid two-week foundation: six runs, no significant pain, and consistent execution. That's not small — that's the kind of disciplined, patient work that leads to durable returns. Next week, we'll assess whether a small time increase is appropriate based on how this week's foot response goes.\",\"perceived_effort\":3}]}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
  "modelId": "\"claude-sonnet-4-6\"",
